30:15.861 --> 30:16.021
It is.

30:16.741 --> 30:18.904
I mean, there isn't anything like an American Indian zone.

30:19.204 --> 30:27.192
No, it was a unique historical phenomenon in the sense that it was a recent literature, a very compressed literary development.

30:27.212 --> 30:28.874
So reclaimable, if you work with it.

30:28.894 --> 30:30.756
Yeah, it was a very compressed literary development.

30:30.816 --> 30:37.283
All these titles, 40,000 titles in a period of 60 or 70 years, were published in large numbers.

30:37.972 --> 30:44.922
and then quickly the literature's cut off the population and potentially destroyed and then the books remain as the record of that culture.

30:44.942 --> 30:54.536
I'm not sure it's... You don't know whether this furnishes an example, say, for some... Oh, I would like to think it does, but I'm not sure any other cultures are going to yield a million books.

30:54.556 --> 30:56.939
I'm not sure any other cultures... Are millions, I wonder?

30:57.200 --> 31:00.845
Well, I don't think any other cultures have that kind of disruption.

31:00.865 --> 31:03.709
Again, the fact that Yiddish never had a country in that sense, Yiddish is

31:04.617 --> 31:08.742
I was just going to say almost unique because I was thinking of Romani as the other.

31:08.762 --> 31:10.744
I don't know if there's one of the universe.

31:10.764 --> 31:12.326
I don't know the answer to that.

31:13.147 --> 31:19.534
But Yiddish is certainly unique as a strong literary tradition for a language without a country.

31:19.554 --> 31:24.480
Another characteristic point is almost the same thing with the Esperanto, which works on these books in Toronto.

31:24.500 --> 31:26.061
But that was almost a Jewish invention.

31:26.121 --> 31:31.047
They said that the Esperanto conventions and war started in the 1930s.

31:31.448 --> 31:40.601
You want to do the collecting stories like the next time?

31:40.722 --> 31:42.845
Yeah, we'll do that in another question.

31:42.865 --> 31:45.248
Because I think we've hit a lot of excellent things.

31:45.268 --> 31:45.529
Good.

31:45.649 --> 31:48.132
And this will give me a chance really to assess what we've done.

31:48.232 --> 31:48.893
That's fine.

31:48.934 --> 31:49.995
Okay.

31:50.676 --> 31:53.019
More detailed questions.

31:53.040 --> 31:54.081
In the meantime,

31:54.584 --> 31:57.110
I'll tell you people are holy open.

31:57.170 --> 31:58.173
Yeah, my work's out of here.

31:58.193 --> 32:00.278
You should do it through here.

32:00.298 --> 32:03.605
You might mention that you should talk to me.

32:03.625 --> 32:04.127
Yeah.

32:04.307 --> 32:06.232
Justice, is my computer here today?

32:08.116 --> 32:09.840
No, it's your Monday when it's your birthday.

32:09.860 --> 32:10.361
I haven't seen it at all.

32:10.382 --> 32:10.602
Okay, yeah.

32:11.138 --> 32:15.305
I just came back from there.

32:15.385 --> 32:21.034
I spent almost a month there.

32:23.157 --> 32:33.814
We started getting a lot of requests from Jews and Soviet Union, asking us to go up, staying there, starting schools, starting cultural centers, and looking for the books to read.

32:33.834 --> 32:35.356
So we would respond to this.

32:35.376 --> 32:37.720
We would send them free to charge any books they needed.

32:38.223 --> 32:40.045
I thought it had been cut off for 72 years.

32:40.125 --> 32:42.629
It was illegal to own these books and suddenly had a chance.

32:43.730 --> 32:44.611
We would do what we could.

32:45.292 --> 32:52.561
We went there at the very end of November, spent close to a month traveling around, meeting these people in person.

32:52.581 --> 32:55.225
And what we found was a very disturbing situation, in a way.

32:55.245 --> 32:56.626
It wasn't what we expected.

32:56.646 --> 33:04.556
We kind of had this notion that here was a community poised and ready for some kind of cultural renaissance and that we could bring large numbers of books in.

33:04.576 --> 33:07.420
This would be a million and a half Jews suddenly coming to life together.

33:08.446 --> 33:09.507
Well, that wasn't the case.

33:09.527 --> 33:10.388
There were two factors.

33:10.408 --> 33:12.650
And one is that assimilation is extreme.

33:12.670 --> 33:15.513
After 72 years, several generations are being cut off.

33:16.074 --> 33:19.397
There's very little knowledge left in the community to build upon.

33:19.417 --> 33:23.141
And the other is that anti-Semitism is so extreme that many Jews are getting out of it.

33:23.161 --> 33:27.405
Most Jews were there trying to leave at this point.

33:27.425 --> 33:31.950
So I guess I don't see a huge future there.

33:31.970 --> 33:37.255
On the other hand, particularly in the Baltics, there is some very interesting activity.

33:37.538 --> 33:44.848
In the Baltics that started Jewish schools, teachers who were trained in Yiddish and Hebrew teachers' academies before the war have organized new schools.

33:44.888 --> 33:45.869
They're not Jewish schools.

33:46.089 --> 33:49.694
They're beginning to teach and study, you know, teach young kids.

33:49.835 --> 33:52.057
You're going to have 400 kids that don't even read us, that mean Yiddish.

33:53.399 --> 33:54.921
So in those places, they're desperate for books.

33:55.883 --> 34:05.115
The way in which books are rare there, I mean, it appears to your eyes when the school in Riga just opened its doors in September, they have one Jewish music book, one Yiddish music book,

34:05.433 --> 34:07.315
which they keep wrapped up in special taping.

34:07.336 --> 34:10.980
The music teacher carries her with her wherever she goes, the only book in the school.

34:11.000 --> 34:18.230
And they had no Yiddish textbooks to use to teach kids.

34:18.250 --> 34:22.155
And so one of the teachers put together a book on her own.

34:22.275 --> 34:24.498
She had no Yiddish type, a Hebrew type.

34:24.518 --> 34:27.162
So she hand-wrote part of the book.

34:27.182 --> 34:33.330
And the rest of it, she took all the books that she had and cut them up and pasted them together in like an extortion note and reconstructed a new book.

34:33.800 --> 34:40.208
and they printed it on the press of the Central Committee of the Communist Party in Latvia, and that's the textbook period.

34:40.628 --> 34:44.052
So you are making... We're going to bring them books.

34:44.133 --> 34:45.214
It's not a token.

34:45.254 --> 34:46.095
No, no, it's a real thing.

34:46.115 --> 34:47.937
It's not a token thing.

34:47.997 --> 34:48.778
It's a very real thing.

34:48.838 --> 34:50.961
Are you bringing them, or are you donating them?

34:51.762 --> 34:58.390
It's a very real thing, which will make a very real difference to a limited number of people, but it won't change the face of the Jewish community of the Soviet Union.

34:58.410 --> 35:00.012
How many books do you think you've got to play so far?

35:00.032 --> 35:01.073
I think about 8,000 or 9,000.

35:01.863 --> 35:03.085
And we'll bring them ourselves.

35:03.105 --> 35:04.888
You know, to ship them is not reliable.

35:04.908 --> 35:05.529
They don't get delivered.

35:06.350 --> 35:08.173
And so we're actually going to bring the books in.

35:08.593 --> 35:22.916
We'll ship the books as far as Stockholm, load them onto a truck in Stockholm, ship the truck on a boat, bring the truck as far as it is, Palo and Origa, coming to the country that way, and then driving around the street with things.

35:22.936 --> 35:25.440
How do you, Maccabib, is that how you pronounce her name?

35:25.460 --> 35:27.002
The woman I hope you're talking about?

35:27.022 --> 35:27.583
Oh, Maccabib.

35:27.952 --> 35:30.715
M-A-C-C-A-B-I-B.

35:31.536 --> 35:34.479
M-A-C-C-A-B-I-B.

35:34.699 --> 35:38.043
Maccabib. Right.

35:38.063 --> 35:39.024
I'm going to switch sides now. Okay.

35:39.204 --> 35:42.467
Part of the reason we've been successful here is because our focus has been books.

35:46.191 --> 35:51.597
To speak about Yiddish culture, the abstract, to speak about books in particular.

35:52.268 --> 35:57.634
I think many people share that love of books, that love of the written word, which is why this book, your book, will work so well, I think.

35:57.654 --> 35:58.234
I hope so.

36:00.417 --> 36:07.084
You know, I just go back to when Holden Reckman told me that they didn't think it would appeal to a limited number of people.

36:07.124 --> 36:07.665
They don't know.

36:07.685 --> 36:09.306
I mean, they don't know.

36:09.326 --> 36:13.010
We're not talking about a Sunday football game, but there are a lot of people who love books, I mean, who love books.

36:13.651 --> 36:20.959
They love, and collecting has never been more popular than it is now, trying to do this without crushing it.

36:21.749 --> 36:35.284
I have a pretty large library at home, but I've been much less concerned about collecting books because having a million books sitting in a warehouse, one would be a little less enthusiastic about adding to the books.

36:35.344 --> 36:37.426
Now I only buy books that I read at this point.

36:37.446 --> 36:38.508
I was going to say, how about yourself?

36:38.528 --> 36:39.168
What do you read?

36:39.409 --> 36:40.250
I read a great deal.

36:40.830 --> 36:42.352
I tend to read literature.

36:42.392 --> 36:45.175
I almost never read modern novels.

36:45.998 --> 36:49.061
From various literary... Oh, sure.

36:49.081 --> 36:56.027
I mean, I still read Yiddish literature, of course, but I also read a great deal of English and French and a lot of other literatures as well.

36:57.728 --> 37:04.754
Everybody from Zola to...anyway, I mean, all great literature I love, and I can read endlessly.

37:05.174 --> 37:08.277
If I had nothing else to do, I would read for the next three years.

37:08.858 --> 37:13.742
You do go up to Nova Scotia, I understand, a couple of weeks just to... Yeah, summer hustle.

37:13.762 --> 37:15.263
And it just allows you to... Right.

37:16.272 --> 37:20.744
But I imagine this is never far from your mind, though.

37:20.764 --> 37:21.366
Oh, the work?

37:21.386 --> 37:22.047
Yeah.

37:22.448 --> 37:23.832
Checking into the office every two days.

37:23.892 --> 37:24.594
It's a busy place.

37:26.399 --> 37:26.880
Okay.

37:27.281 --> 37:28.124
Good.

37:28.144 --> 37:28.645
I'll be back.

